WEBVTT

1
00:01:32.592 --> 00:01:34.468
(MACHINE WHIRRING)

2
00:01:39.265 --> 00:01:40.974
(MACHINE DINGS)

3
00:02:09.963 --> 00:02:13.257
(BOTH SPEAKING NORWEGIAN)

4
00:02:18.138 --> 00:02:19.680
(JORGEN LAUGHS IN DISBELIEF)

5
00:02:21.349 --> 00:02:23.308
(BOTH LAUGHING)

6
00:02:42.829 --> 00:02:46.498
It gives me great pleasure to welcome
the director of the Institute

7
00:02:46.583 --> 00:02:47.749
and my old friend.

8
00:02:47.834 --> 00:02:49.668
Dr. Andreas Jacobsen.

9
00:02:50.336 --> 00:02:52.546
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

10
00:02:58.052 --> 00:02:59.052
Thank you.

11
00:03:01.931 --> 00:03:04.266
Thank you. Thank you. Dr. Pereira.

12
00:03:05.018 --> 00:03:08.103
Seventy-five years ago.
Ms. Nellie Edvardsen.

13
00:03:08.438 --> 00:03:11.690
overcome with guilt by the fortune
her late husband's family had amassed

14
00:03:11.983 --> 00:03:14.610
producing mustard gas
during World War I.

15
00:03:14.944 --> 00:03:16.778
founded our Institute

16
00:03:17.113 --> 00:03:20.449
so that the wonders of science
could instead be used to help mankind.

17
00:03:21.201 --> 00:03:22.868
In the 1950s.

18
00:03:23.203 --> 00:03:26.788
the Institute identified overpopulation

19
00:03:27.123 --> 00:03:30.709
as mankind's single greatest
long-term threat.

20
00:03:31.044 --> 00:03:33.503
The cause of all the catastrophes
we are seeing today:

21
00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:35.881
Extreme climate and weather events.

22
00:03:35.965 --> 00:03:39.635
and the devastating impact on
food and water security.

23
00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:43.805
Among the many solutions
we conceived so many years ago.

24
00:03:44.140 --> 00:03:48.685
one. which seemed then so ambitious.
so out of our grasp.

25
00:03:49.187 --> 00:03:51.021
has finally borne fruit.

26
00:03:51.397 --> 00:03:53.315
And today. we are proud to unveil

27
00:03:53.399 --> 00:03:56.151
what we fervently believe
to be the only practical.

28
00:03:56.236 --> 00:03:58.278
humane and inclusive remedy

29
00:03:58.363 --> 00:04:00.572
to humanity's gravest problem.

30
00:04:01.157 --> 00:04:05.452
My colleague. Dr. Jorgen Asbjørnsen.
will now present his findings.

31
00:04:06.329 --> 00:04:07.996
Are you ready. Doctor?

32
00:04:08.331 --> 00:04:09.831
JORGEN: Yes. I'm ready.

33
00:04:16.881 --> 00:04:18.882
(AUDIENCE GASPING)

34
00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:21.718
(AUDIENCE MURMURING)

35
00:04:35.900 --> 00:04:37.359
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

36
00:04:37.443 --> 00:04:39.278
ANDREAS: Please take your seats.

37
00:04:41.114 --> 00:04:43.115
Please sit down.
ladies and gentlemen. please.

38
00:04:43.616 --> 00:04:45.200
Please take your seats.
ladies and gentlemen.

39
00:04:45.285 --> 00:04:47.119
Thank you very much. Thank you.

40
00:04:47.787 --> 00:04:49.371
Thank you. thank you.

41
00:04:55.295 --> 00:04:58.380
Dr. Pereira. esteemed colleagues.

42
00:04:59.882 --> 00:05:04.720
Five years ago. building on the research
of our predecessors at the Institute.

43
00:05:05.221 --> 00:05:07.848
my team and I discovered a process

44
00:05:07.932 --> 00:05:12.269
by which all organic material
can be reduced at the cellular level

45
00:05:12.603 --> 00:05:17.983
by a ratio of approximately 2.744 to 1.

46
00:05:18.985 --> 00:05:22.487
Such a process converts
a man of 1.8 meters

47
00:05:22.655 --> 00:05:25.741
to just 12.9 centimeters.

48
00:05:26.159 --> 00:05:30.996
A wide array of flora and fauna
were subjected in this process.

49
00:05:31.414 --> 00:05:34.833
and. with the exception
of some fish and shellfish.

50
00:05:35.084 --> 00:05:38.754
absolutely no side effects
were detected.

51
00:05:39.422 --> 00:05:40.589
Please. lights.

52
00:05:43.843 --> 00:05:47.304
Once the safety of
the procedure was confirmed.

53
00:05:47.472 --> 00:05:52.267
36 brave volunteers joined
my wife Anne-Helene and me

54
00:05:52.352 --> 00:05:56.146
as the very first humans
to undergo cellular reduction.

55
00:05:56.230 --> 00:05:58.982
The process is short and painless.

56
00:05:59.067 --> 00:06:00.859
with only the mild discomfort of

57
00:06:01.194 --> 00:06:05.280
removal and replacement of dental
and other prosthetics.

58
00:06:05.448 --> 00:06:08.658
The subjects are placed
under light sedation

59
00:06:08.743 --> 00:06:13.455
and after a brief rest.
fully recover within an hour or two.

60
00:06:13.706 --> 00:06:15.624
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

61
00:06:20.088 --> 00:06:24.716
Once completed. our little village.
just 7 meters by 11 meters.

62
00:06:25.093 --> 00:06:28.845
was placed inside
a gas-permeable enclosure

63
00:06:29.055 --> 00:06:31.973
designed to protect us
from the hazards of

64
00:06:32.141 --> 00:06:35.143
weather. animals and insects.

65
00:06:35.478 --> 00:06:37.396
Thus. we set about to live together

66
00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:42.484
in the world's very first
self-sustaining community of the small.

67
00:06:44.904 --> 00:06:47.072
I hold here in my hand

68
00:06:47.240 --> 00:06:52.911
all of the uncompostable waste
produced by 36 people over four years.

69
00:06:53.871 --> 00:06:55.372
(APPLAUSE)

70
00:07:01.504 --> 00:07:04.089
In this afternoon's session.
we will outline our proposal

71
00:07:04.173 --> 00:07:07.342
for a two to three hundred-year
transition

72
00:07:07.427 --> 00:07:10.429
for the world to transform
from big into small.

73
00:07:11.013 --> 00:07:12.347
But for now.

74
00:07:12.849 --> 00:07:16.017
I'd like you all to meet some
very special people. Come.

75
00:07:21.232 --> 00:07:22.357
MAN: Bravo!

76
00:07:25.361 --> 00:07:27.070
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

77
00:07:47.633 --> 00:07:50.802
And look. there is little Ronni Nestrud.

78
00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:53.513
the first small baby ever born.

79
00:07:53.973 --> 00:07:57.142
and his new little sister Ulrikke.

80
00:08:12.283 --> 00:08:14.993
(REPORTER 1 SPEAKING KOREAN ON TV)

81
00:08:21.250 --> 00:08:23.043
(INAUDIBLE CONVERSATIONS)

82
00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:27.756
(REPORTER 2 SPEAKING SPANISH ON TV)

83
00:08:29.842 --> 00:08:32.010
(REPORTER 3 SPEAKING
OTHER LANGUAGE ON RADIO)

84
00:08:34.472 --> 00:08:37.140
(REPORTER 4 SPEAKING
OTHER LANGUAGE ON TV)

85
00:08:38.434 --> 00:08:40.352
(REPORTER 5 SPEAKING
OTHER LANGUAGE ON TV)

86
00:08:41.896 --> 00:08:43.855
(REPORTER 6 SPEAKING
OTHER LANGUAGE ON TV)

87
00:08:47.693 --> 00:08:49.778
<i>REPORTER 7: (ON TV) Jorgen Asbjørnsen
of the Edvardsen Institute.</i>

88
00:08:49.862 --> 00:08:53.114
<i>himself now only 10 centimeters tall
and weighing just 18 grams.</i>

89
00:08:53.407 --> 00:08:55.158
<i>explained the rationale
behind the invention.</i>

90
00:08:55.284 --> 00:08:56.284
Wow!

91
00:08:56.369 --> 00:08:59.287
That is wild. isn't it? Just wild.

92
00:08:59.789 --> 00:09:00.872
Say. Holly?

93
00:09:00.957 --> 00:09:03.667
You can go ahead and put
the takeout order in. Thanks.

94
00:09:03.918 --> 00:09:05.502
(REPORTER CONTINUES INDISTINCTLY)

95
00:09:25.398 --> 00:09:27.524
- KAY: Is that you?
- Yeah.

96
00:09:29.402 --> 00:09:30.735
You hungry?

97
00:09:30.861 --> 00:09:33.238
I ate about an hour ago.

98
00:09:33.531 --> 00:09:35.240
I didn't know when you were coming.

99
00:09:35.408 --> 00:09:36.950
You knew I was bringing food.

100
00:09:37.034 --> 00:09:39.452
I called you and asked you specifically.
and then you go and eat?

101
00:09:39.537 --> 00:09:41.830
Just a sesame chicken! I'm still hungry.

102
00:09:42.164 --> 00:09:44.332
(TV CONTINUES PLAYING)

103
00:09:48.421 --> 00:09:50.088
Did you see the news today?

104
00:09:50.172 --> 00:09:53.174
- About the little Swedish man?
- Norwegian.

105
00:09:53.926 --> 00:09:57.387
Helen called to tell me
to turn on the TV.

106
00:09:57.471 --> 00:09:58.930
What won't they think of next?

107
00:09:59.015 --> 00:10:00.015
Unbelievable.

108
00:10:00.099 --> 00:10:02.058
Biggest thing since landing
on the moon. Bigger!

109
00:10:02.143 --> 00:10:04.352
(GRUNTS) I don't get it.

110
00:10:04.437 --> 00:10:07.230
Why would anybody
want to do that to himself?

111
00:10:07.857 --> 00:10:09.941
They can shrink people down

112
00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:12.193
and fly to Mars.

113
00:10:13.029 --> 00:10:15.864
but they can't cure my fibromyalgia?

114
00:10:16.616 --> 00:10:17.949
(EXHALES)

115
00:10:18.534 --> 00:10:21.286
And all this fuss about the environment

116
00:10:21.621 --> 00:10:24.414
as though the world's
going to end tomorrow.

117
00:10:25.625 --> 00:10:27.292
I'm in pain.

118
00:10:27.793 --> 00:10:30.879
I can't breathe! Doesn't that matter?

119
00:10:31.213 --> 00:10:33.548
Lots of people are in pain. Mom.

120
00:10:34.550 --> 00:10:36.301
in all sorts of ways.

121
00:11:04.705 --> 00:11:06.414
(PAUL SPEAKING SPANISH)

122
00:11:07.958 --> 00:11:09.459
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

123
00:11:13.422 --> 00:11:14.422
...tingling?

124
00:11:14.507 --> 00:11:16.007
- More like tingling.
- Tingling. okay.

125
00:11:17.635 --> 00:11:20.804
<i>MAN: (ON TV) This downsizing thing
is simply runaway-train technology</i>

126
00:11:21.097 --> 00:11:24.391
<i>that's having a devastating impact
on our world economy.</i>

127
00:11:24.725 --> 00:11:27.894
<i>We're losing billions of dollars
in consumer spending already.</i>

128
00:11:28.187 --> 00:11:30.563
<i>It's hurting us
in construction. automobile.</i>

129
00:11:30.648 --> 00:11:31.940
<i>housing and defense.</i>

130
00:11:32.024 --> 00:11:33.900
<i>And then. of course.
when we get to politics?</i>

131
00:11:34.026 --> 00:11:36.194
<i>Israelis shrinking Palestinians.</i>

132
00:11:36.278 --> 00:11:38.697
<i>African dictators shrinking
rival ethnic groups.</i>

133
00:11:38.948 --> 00:11:42.033
<i>Look. Ron. in any major
transformation of society.</i>

134
00:11:42.118 --> 00:11:44.869
<i>are there serious growing pains? Sure.</i>

135
00:11:45.037 --> 00:11:49.082
<i>But at current mass and volume.
human life on Earth is unsustainable.</i>

136
00:11:50.042 --> 00:11:52.043
You know. that one guy
makes a good point.

137
00:11:52.128 --> 00:11:54.504
This family on my block
just moved away to get small.

138
00:11:54.588 --> 00:11:56.131
Now their house is just sitting there.

139
00:11:56.215 --> 00:11:59.342
Making everybody's values take
a dive is what they're doing

140
00:11:59.427 --> 00:12:01.511
and just when I'm trying to refinance.

141
00:12:01.679 --> 00:12:04.264
Marlene thinks I should do it
just to lose the weight.

142
00:12:04.348 --> 00:12:05.807
(ALL LAUGHING)

143
00:12:06.475 --> 00:12:08.226
TIM: You and me both. buddy.

144
00:12:08.519 --> 00:12:10.937
Hey. Dee. is that
takeout order about ready?

145
00:12:13.649 --> 00:12:15.817
Hey. honey. I brought food!

146
00:12:15.901 --> 00:12:17.485
AUDREY: I'm not hungry.

147
00:12:25.411 --> 00:12:26.661
PAUL: What's wrong?

148
00:12:27.079 --> 00:12:29.080
I have a splitting headache.

149
00:12:29.415 --> 00:12:30.749
The store was super busy.

150
00:12:30.833 --> 00:12:33.668
and Carla was a total bitch on wheels.

151
00:12:33.753 --> 00:12:35.587
I feel like I'm going to throw up.

152
00:12:35.921 --> 00:12:37.505
PAUL: Here. let me do the neck thing.

153
00:12:38.090 --> 00:12:40.592
(SIGHS) Yeah. do the little neck thing.

154
00:12:41.635 --> 00:12:42.761
Mmm.

155
00:12:42.845 --> 00:12:44.429
PAUL: Just relax. honey.

156
00:12:45.514 --> 00:12:47.182
Let me take all the weight.

157
00:12:49.101 --> 00:12:51.603
<i>REALTOR: Okay. here is
the beautiful formal living room</i>

158
00:12:51.729 --> 00:12:53.772
with the wonderful fireplace.

159
00:12:54.190 --> 00:12:56.858
And come around here. and we have

160
00:12:56.942 --> 00:12:59.360
the nice big breakfast area
for the kitchen.

161
00:12:59.445 --> 00:13:01.112
Big eating area.

162
00:13:01.614 --> 00:13:04.783
And this kitchen is just a complete wow.

163
00:13:05.576 --> 00:13:07.327
No. it's awesome. I just think

164
00:13:07.411 --> 00:13:09.662
maybe we should look again
at that place in Benson.

165
00:13:10.039 --> 00:13:11.873
Come on. let's just check out the rest.

166
00:13:11.957 --> 00:13:13.208
This is great in here.

167
00:13:13.459 --> 00:13:15.877
Double oven. six-burner gas stove.

168
00:13:16.128 --> 00:13:18.838
<i>It's got this wonderful
butler's pantry over here.</i>

169
00:13:18.923 --> 00:13:20.590
<i>granite counter top...</i>

170
00:13:42.029 --> 00:13:43.696
(CALCULATOR WHIRS)

171
00:13:46.575 --> 00:13:47.742
(SIGHS)

172
00:13:56.794 --> 00:13:58.211
(CAR LOCK BEEPS)

173
00:13:59.672 --> 00:14:01.506
- Oh. hey. Sean.
- Oh. hey. Paul. How you doing?

174
00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:02.590
Good.

175
00:14:04.969 --> 00:14:08.137
PAUL: Do I look fat?
AUDREY: No. you look very handsome.

176
00:14:09.265 --> 00:14:11.641
- (MUSIC PLAYING)
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

177
00:14:12.142 --> 00:14:13.560
PAUL: Anesthesiology. huh?

178
00:14:14.186 --> 00:14:16.479
My wife says I put people to
sleep even without the drugs.

179
00:14:16.564 --> 00:14:17.605
(ALL CHUCKLE)

180
00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:19.357
I'm surprised you're still awake.

181
00:14:19.525 --> 00:14:21.776
He uses that joke like twice a week.

182
00:14:22.444 --> 00:14:24.904
- What's your field. Paul?
- Occupational therapy.

183
00:14:24.989 --> 00:14:27.365
- Okay.
- Oh. Like career counseling?

184
00:14:27.533 --> 00:14:29.492
Uh. no. it's just like physical therapy.

185
00:14:29.577 --> 00:14:32.370
but focused on
workplace injuries and rehab.

186
00:14:32.538 --> 00:14:35.456
Repetitive stress. lower back.
that sort of thing.

187
00:14:35.541 --> 00:14:36.875
A lot of shoulder problems.

188
00:14:37.209 --> 00:14:39.377
I'm in-house over at Omaha Steaks.

189
00:14:39.545 --> 00:14:41.045
He does a lot of paperwork.

190
00:14:41.213 --> 00:14:43.172
Yeah. well. I get a little
carpal tunnel of my own

191
00:14:43.257 --> 00:14:44.883
- from time to time.
- Tell me about it.

192
00:14:44.967 --> 00:14:47.969
Medicine these days
is all about covering your ass.

193
00:14:48.053 --> 00:14:50.388
Hey. Paul. weren't you pre-med
down in Lincoln?

194
00:14:50.973 --> 00:14:53.141
Good memory. Yeah. I put in two years.

195
00:14:53.225 --> 00:14:54.309
Then my mom got real sick.

196
00:14:54.393 --> 00:14:56.895
so I moved back to Omaha
to take care of her.

197
00:14:58.022 --> 00:15:00.356
<i>I wanted to be a surgeon. actually.</i>

198
00:15:00.441 --> 00:15:02.775
<i>You know. we might've ended up
working together.</i>

199
00:15:03.068 --> 00:15:04.861
<i>You could've been my anesthesiologist!</i>

200
00:15:04.945 --> 00:15:07.155
ANESTHESIOLOGIST: How about that?
PAUL: Yeah.

201
00:15:21.378 --> 00:15:23.713
WOMAN: Oh. my God. No way.

202
00:15:24.590 --> 00:15:27.008
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

203
00:15:38.437 --> 00:15:39.604
PAUL: Dave?

204
00:15:40.773 --> 00:15:42.774
That's Dave! Dave Johnson!

205
00:15:43.025 --> 00:15:44.400
And Carol!

206
00:15:44.944 --> 00:15:47.528
I heard he was coming. I had no idea!

207
00:15:47.696 --> 00:15:50.615
He never struck me as the kind
of guy who'd go get small.

208
00:15:50.950 --> 00:15:52.033
Wow!

209
00:16:07.299 --> 00:16:08.633
- (OVER MEGAPHONE) Hey. everybody.
- Hi.

210
00:16:10.469 --> 00:16:13.137
- Hope we're not intruding.
- ALL: No.

211
00:16:14.306 --> 00:16:15.473
Hey. Andy?

212
00:16:15.891 --> 00:16:17.725
Could you get Carol a...

213
00:16:18.936 --> 00:16:20.061
Gin and tonic.

214
00:16:20.145 --> 00:16:21.646
A gin and tonic.

215
00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:24.148
With lime.

216
00:16:25.109 --> 00:16:26.109
CAROL: Well. actually.

217
00:16:26.193 --> 00:16:28.027
<i>we weren't planning on coming
at all at first.</i>

218
00:16:28.237 --> 00:16:30.822
but then. you know. we started
getting all the emails.

219
00:16:30.990 --> 00:16:33.491
Plus my sister was having
a lump removed.

220
00:16:33.575 --> 00:16:36.577
She's fine. thank God.
but I still needed to see her.

221
00:16:36.912 --> 00:16:38.329
So what's traveling like?

222
00:16:38.414 --> 00:16:40.331
How'd you guys get up here
from New Mexico?

223
00:16:40.749 --> 00:16:42.125
CAROL: Oh. gosh. it's great! Yeah.

224
00:16:42.209 --> 00:16:44.794
The airlines are getting
more and more small-friendly.

225
00:16:45.045 --> 00:16:46.796
All the seats are first-class.

226
00:16:47.047 --> 00:16:49.674
DAVE: So. after a couple of years
in Florida. we moved out to Vegas.

227
00:16:50.009 --> 00:16:52.343
Yeah. I think that's
the last time we talked.

228
00:16:52.428 --> 00:16:54.971
Yeah. Well. Vegas wasn't
such a good choice for me.

229
00:16:55.055 --> 00:16:56.097
as it turns out.

230
00:16:56.181 --> 00:16:59.183
Got into some real bad habits.
Pretty much hit rock bottom.

231
00:16:59.435 --> 00:17:01.936
I'll tell you. any other woman
would've run for the hills.

232
00:17:02.021 --> 00:17:05.189
But Carol. man. she's a saint.
She stuck with me.

233
00:17:05.607 --> 00:17:07.650
But I really had to come clean
about everything.

234
00:17:07.735 --> 00:17:08.943
I mean everything.

235
00:17:09.278 --> 00:17:10.778
You know. almost.

236
00:17:11.196 --> 00:17:12.864
So the decision to...

237
00:17:13.115 --> 00:17:15.950
Well. that's the thing.
We both needed a change.

238
00:17:16.035 --> 00:17:18.119
Hit the reset button. Start all over.

239
00:17:18.537 --> 00:17:21.247
Well. plus. it must feel good to know
you're really making a difference.

240
00:17:21.623 --> 00:17:23.541
You mean all that crap
about saving the planet?

241
00:17:23.625 --> 00:17:24.625
Yeah.

242
00:17:24.710 --> 00:17:27.378
Downsizing is about saving yourself.

243
00:17:27.713 --> 00:17:29.088
It takes the pressure right off.

244
00:17:29.173 --> 00:17:30.298
especially money pressure.

245
00:17:30.632 --> 00:17:33.926
I'm just not driven and ambitious
like the rest of my family.

246
00:17:34.261 --> 00:17:36.596
But now Carol and I. we live like kings!

247
00:17:36.972 --> 00:17:39.640
I'm still living in
the same house I grew up in.

248
00:17:39.892 --> 00:17:43.561
Audrey's dying for us to move.
but we're really strapped.

249
00:17:43.771 --> 00:17:47.106
I mean. shit. I just finished
paying off my student loans!

250
00:17:47.316 --> 00:17:48.858
Yeah. well...

251
00:17:49.568 --> 00:17:52.153
Listen. if you ever start
thinking about it seriously.

252
00:17:52.488 --> 00:17:54.155
here's my two cents.

253
00:17:54.323 --> 00:17:56.741
There's a lot of small communities
cropping up out there.

254
00:17:56.992 --> 00:17:57.992
but don't mess around.

255
00:17:58.077 --> 00:17:59.494
Leisureland's where you want to be.

256
00:17:59.912 --> 00:18:02.747
Best houses. best appliances.
best doctors.

257
00:18:02.956 --> 00:18:04.540
They book all the big concert tours.

258
00:18:04.625 --> 00:18:05.792
Got all the great restaurants.

259
00:18:06.085 --> 00:18:08.002
The kids love Cheesecake Factory

260
00:18:08.087 --> 00:18:09.921
and Leisureland's got three of them.

261
00:18:10.422 --> 00:18:12.507
And hey. I'm not just saying all this
for the referral credit.

262
00:18:12.591 --> 00:18:13.591
just so you know.

263
00:18:16.095 --> 00:18:18.805
AUDREY: I liked little Carol.
She's got a lot on the ball.

264
00:18:18.889 --> 00:18:20.973
She's reading books
she's always wanted to read.

265
00:18:21.058 --> 00:18:22.225
she's taking Italian.

266
00:18:22.643 --> 00:18:25.978
- And she's never been fitter.
- Well. they sure seem happy.

267
00:18:26.146 --> 00:18:28.564
Dave says he's getting
pretty good on the drums.

268
00:18:28.982 --> 00:18:30.983
Next year they're taking
the kids out of school

269
00:18:31.068 --> 00:18:34.070
to spend six months
at a sister city in Tuscany.

270
00:18:34.196 --> 00:18:38.116
Cooking classes. yoga. wine tasting.
the whole nine yards.

271
00:18:40.577 --> 00:18:42.453
(ANSWERING MACHINE BEEPS)

272
00:18:42.871 --> 00:18:44.872
<i>(ON ANSWERING MACHINE)
Hi. Saf. Audrey. It's Milo.</i>

273
00:18:45.207 --> 00:18:46.415
<i>Bad news.</i>

274
00:18:46.500 --> 00:18:49.043
<i>Your mortgage application at
First National bounced back.</i>

275
00:18:49.378 --> 00:18:51.921
<i>The underwriter didn't like
the income-to-debt ratios.</i>

276
00:18:52.005 --> 00:18:53.548
<i>they're a little excessive.</i>

277
00:18:53.882 --> 00:18:55.341
<i>I don't know if you guys
can come up with</i>

278
00:18:55.425 --> 00:18:57.552
<i>another ten. fifteen percent down?</i>

279
00:18:57.636 --> 00:18:59.804
<i>If you could maybe
boost it up a little bit...</i>

280
00:18:59.888 --> 00:19:02.807
I bet we'll be able to tell right away
if it's for us or not.

281
00:19:03.142 --> 00:19:05.143
Yeah. so let's not waste a lot of time.

282
00:19:05.477 --> 00:19:08.062
Maybe if we get to Santa Fe early.
we can get a massage.

283
00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:09.730
Sounds good to me.

284
00:19:30.961 --> 00:19:32.712
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

285
00:19:33.297 --> 00:19:34.547
<i>(CHEEK TO CHEEK PLAYING)</i>

286
00:20:06.955 --> 00:20:08.831
(MUSIC PLAYING)

287
00:20:10.626 --> 00:20:11.959
Welcome. everybody!

288
00:20:12.211 --> 00:20:14.670
I'm Jeff Lonowski.
Senior Product Specialist

289
00:20:14.755 --> 00:20:16.881
and happy homeowner
here at Leisureland Estates.

290
00:20:17.132 --> 00:20:18.799
You having a good time?

291
00:20:18.884 --> 00:20:20.384
- AUDIENCE: Yeah.
- (SCATTERED APPLAUSE)

292
00:20:21.553 --> 00:20:24.305
Come on. guys. You're a heck
of a lot bigger than I am.

293
00:20:24.473 --> 00:20:27.225
Make some noise!
Are you having a good time?

294
00:20:27.851 --> 00:20:29.143
(ALL CHEERING LOUDLY)

295
00:20:30.187 --> 00:20:31.312
- Yeah!
- Yeah!

296
00:20:31.396 --> 00:20:33.397
JEFF: That's more like it.

297
00:20:33.732 --> 00:20:35.650
So. what do you think of my place?

298
00:20:35.734 --> 00:20:36.817
(MURMURING AND WHISTLING)

299
00:20:36.902 --> 00:20:38.402
Pretty nifty. huh?

300
00:20:38.695 --> 00:20:40.363
It's the house of my dreams.

301
00:20:40.572 --> 00:20:42.865
Heck. I'd say this is
the house of anybody's dreams!

302
00:20:43.033 --> 00:20:44.533
Why. an average guy like me

303
00:20:44.701 --> 00:20:46.285
would have to work 20. 30.

304
00:20:46.370 --> 00:20:48.788
maybe 40 years to afford
a place like this.

305
00:20:48.872 --> 00:20:50.122
if ever!

306
00:20:50.457 --> 00:20:53.209
And just wait till you see
what's inside.

307
00:20:55.837 --> 00:20:57.463
(AUDIENCE GASPING)

308
00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:02.927
Oh!

309
00:21:03.387 --> 00:21:04.720
LAURA: Jeff!

310
00:21:05.389 --> 00:21:08.724
You've got to stop inviting guests over
without telling me.

311
00:21:08.892 --> 00:21:10.559
Oh. sorry. Laura. I was only...

312
00:21:10.727 --> 00:21:14.563
I mean. I finally just got in the tub
to relax after such a busy day.

313
00:21:14.731 --> 00:21:16.232
JEFF: Busy doing what. sweetheart?

314
00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:17.608
Oh. no end of things.

315
00:21:17.693 --> 00:21:19.819
First I took a tennis lesson
and had a massage.

316
00:21:19.903 --> 00:21:20.903
JEFF: Nice.

317
00:21:20.988 --> 00:21:23.364
And then after a gourmet lunch
with the girls.

318
00:21:23.532 --> 00:21:25.283
well. we couldn't help
ourselves. so we popped

319
00:21:25.367 --> 00:21:27.660
into that new Loget
jewelry store downtown.

320
00:21:27.744 --> 00:21:28.744
Uh-oh.

321
00:21:28.829 --> 00:21:31.205
Loget? What's that gonna cost me?

322
00:21:31.373 --> 00:21:33.499
- (AUDIENCE LAUGHING)
- Now. Jeff. you hush!

323
00:21:33.667 --> 00:21:35.668
I was really good.

324
00:21:36.378 --> 00:21:38.713
Just another diamond bracelet.

325
00:21:38.839 --> 00:21:40.047
(AUDIENCE GASPING)

326
00:21:40.132 --> 00:21:42.883
"Just a diamond bracelet"?
That doesn't sound like you.

327
00:21:43.802 --> 00:21:46.971
You're right. I don't like
to break up a set.

328
00:21:47.055 --> 00:21:49.724
so I got matching diamond earrings

329
00:21:50.142 --> 00:21:52.101
and a matching diamond necklace.

330
00:21:52.644 --> 00:21:55.146
All conflict-free and set in platinum.

331
00:21:55.480 --> 00:21:56.731
JEFF: How much. Laura?

332
00:21:56.815 --> 00:21:59.233
Aw. but. Jeff. they look so good on me.
and you should see...

333
00:21:59.318 --> 00:22:00.818
How much. Laura?

334
00:22:00.986 --> 00:22:03.821
- Well. Jeff...
- I said. how much?

335
00:22:04.281 --> 00:22:05.656
$83.

336
00:22:06.033 --> 00:22:07.116
JEFF: $83!

337
00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:08.200
- Are you crazy?
- Oh!

338
00:22:08.368 --> 00:22:11.704
Why. that's practically our food budget
for two whole months!

339
00:22:11.830 --> 00:22:12.997
(AUDIENCE GASPING)

340
00:22:13.081 --> 00:22:14.415
(PEOPLE APPLAUDING)

341
00:22:49.743 --> 00:22:52.036
<i>SALESPERSON: Putting it all together.
if you liquidate</i>

342
00:22:52.120 --> 00:22:54.580
your current home. cars and other assets

343
00:22:54.831 --> 00:22:56.832
and purchase the Regency-level estate.

344
00:22:56.917 --> 00:22:59.919
remember. that's
the 12.000-square-foot-equivalent home

345
00:23:00.003 --> 00:23:02.296
on the 1.5-acre-equivalent lot

346
00:23:02.381 --> 00:23:04.673
at a base price of $63.000.

347
00:23:04.925 --> 00:23:06.801
Then the health and fitness package.

348
00:23:06.885 --> 00:23:09.095
that's $4.500.
you're going to want to get that.

349
00:23:09.179 --> 00:23:13.099
It's gym. pool. sauna. steam.
hot tub and a tennis court.

350
00:23:13.266 --> 00:23:15.434
Then the medical procedures
for two adults.

351
00:23:15.519 --> 00:23:16.602
that's $15.000.

352
00:23:16.978 --> 00:23:19.063
Wait. does insurance cover any of that?

353
00:23:19.439 --> 00:23:23.067
No. but at the Regency level.
you qualify for a substantial discount.

354
00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:25.027
And don't forget the federal tax credit.

355
00:23:25.112 --> 00:23:26.195
- Right. Right.
- All right?

356
00:23:26.279 --> 00:23:31.242
So. taking a look at your current debt.
your retirement and your other savings.

357
00:23:31.785 --> 00:23:35.746
you are at $152.000 in equity.

358
00:23:35.872 --> 00:23:38.165
People. that is
a very comfortable number.

359
00:23:38.500 --> 00:23:39.667
"Comfortable"? That doesn't

360
00:23:39.751 --> 00:23:41.085
- sound like nearly enough.
- Yeah.

361
00:23:41.253 --> 00:23:43.421
No. See. you have to look
at this column. Audrey.

362
00:23:43.505 --> 00:23:44.672
Equivalent value.

363
00:23:45.006 --> 00:23:47.341
You're solidly inside
the Blue Chip zone.

364
00:23:47.509 --> 00:23:50.344
In Leisureland. your $152.000

365
00:23:50.512 --> 00:23:53.514
translates to $12.5 million.

366
00:23:53.723 --> 00:23:55.558
To live on. For life.

367
00:23:55.851 --> 00:23:57.601
I mean. come on!

368
00:23:57.936 --> 00:23:58.936
Wow.

369
00:23:59.104 --> 00:24:00.521
(BOTH CHUCKLE NERVOUSLY)

370
00:24:00.605 --> 00:24:03.441
Hold on. If this is such a good thing.
how come you haven't done it?

371
00:24:03.942 --> 00:24:05.443
I would do it in a heartbeat!

372
00:24:05.527 --> 00:24:08.279
But my husband had a hip replacement.
so he's ineligible.

373
00:24:09.114 --> 00:24:10.823
So. what do you think?

374
00:24:11.074 --> 00:24:13.159
Would the Regency level
be your first choice?

375
00:24:13.243 --> 00:24:16.495
Or should I show you something
a little more deluxe?

376
00:24:20.500 --> 00:24:22.084
Honey. why don't you just
go ahead and pick?

377
00:24:22.169 --> 00:24:23.836
I just want you to be happy.

378
00:24:24.629 --> 00:24:25.671
(SQUEALS)

379
00:24:25.755 --> 00:24:28.716
That's a good husband.
Take a look at this.

380
00:24:29.384 --> 00:24:31.886
Hey. how much for the hot dog cooker?

381
00:24:34.306 --> 00:24:35.306
Four dollars?

382
00:24:35.682 --> 00:24:37.183
I'll give you a dollar.

383
00:24:37.601 --> 00:24:38.601
Sold!

384
00:24:38.935 --> 00:24:42.104
Keep up with the exercises.
don't get lazy. Look.

385
00:24:42.439 --> 00:24:43.564
I laminated it for you.

386
00:24:43.648 --> 00:24:45.524
so you literally have
no excuse not to do it.

387
00:24:45.609 --> 00:24:46.609
Okay. Thanks. Paul.

388
00:24:46.693 --> 00:24:47.693
- Thanks a lot.
- You bet.

389
00:24:47.777 --> 00:24:49.069
Maybe someday me and my wife

390
00:24:49.154 --> 00:24:50.613
will get small and we'll
come down to see you.

391
00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:52.865
Well. I'd love that.
but in the meantime...

392
00:24:52.949 --> 00:24:54.033
- Okay?
- All right.

393
00:24:54.117 --> 00:24:56.785
Just 15 minutes every night.
It'll change your life.

394
00:24:56.953 --> 00:24:58.829
- Okay. Thanks. Paul.
- See you. Dave!

395
00:24:58.914 --> 00:25:03.125
BOB: We're here to wish Paul Safranek
farewell as he moves on to Leisureland.

396
00:25:03.210 --> 00:25:05.085
and we wish him nothing but the best.

397
00:25:05.170 --> 00:25:06.921
Good luck to you and Audrey.

398
00:25:07.672 --> 00:25:10.132
- Thanks. Bob. Thanks. Bob.
- (ALL CHEERING)

399
00:25:16.806 --> 00:25:18.807
BARRY: And you guys didn't consider
Treasure Island

400
00:25:18.892 --> 00:25:19.892
out in Palm Desert?

401
00:25:19.976 --> 00:25:21.894
Well. we checked it out. but...

402
00:25:22.062 --> 00:25:24.104
I mean. I liked it all right.
but Audrey thought they were

403
00:25:24.189 --> 00:25:25.397
a little stingy with the amenities.

404
00:25:25.565 --> 00:25:28.108
especially given what they were charging
in monthly maintenance.

405
00:25:28.485 --> 00:25:32.655
And I just turned to Paul and said.
"Okay. you win. Let's go for it. "

406
00:25:33.073 --> 00:25:35.115
We're just gonna miss you so much.

407
00:25:36.243 --> 00:25:38.285
Gina. I'm gonna miss you. too.

408
00:25:39.120 --> 00:25:41.956
Look. it's not like we're dying. Okay?
We're just relocating.

409
00:25:42.290 --> 00:25:45.292
And we'll be back at least
once a year. Maybe more!

410
00:25:45.585 --> 00:25:47.836
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

411
00:25:51.716 --> 00:25:53.467
- Hi. Dad.
- Hi. sweetie.

412
00:25:55.053 --> 00:25:57.805
I'm sorry your mom couldn't
bring herself to come.

413
00:25:57.973 --> 00:25:59.431
but she sends her love.

414
00:25:59.516 --> 00:26:02.059
and we're expecting you
at the house tomorrow afternoon.

415
00:26:03.478 --> 00:26:04.687
Glad you could make it. Larry.

416
00:26:04.771 --> 00:26:07.231
- Hey. Paul.
- What can I get you. Dad?

417
00:26:07.482 --> 00:26:08.566
Um...

418
00:26:08.650 --> 00:26:11.318
Look. why don't I...
Here. you guys visit. I'II...

419
00:26:11.486 --> 00:26:12.486
Beer.

420
00:26:12.737 --> 00:26:15.364
- Just any beer.
- Great. Okay. coming up.

421
00:26:17.534 --> 00:26:19.535
I wish Mom weren't taking this so hard.

422
00:26:19.703 --> 00:26:21.370
Well. you know your mother.

423
00:26:21.621 --> 00:26:25.040
Frankly. I was a little skeptical
about it myself at first.

424
00:26:25.458 --> 00:26:27.376
Say. you remember Jerry Gross?

425
00:26:28.044 --> 00:26:31.630
I called him the other day.
He and Bev retired down there.

426
00:26:31.965 --> 00:26:34.550
Did the whole shrinking thing
you kids are doing.

427
00:26:34.884 --> 00:26:37.595
He says they're getting
along just fine. Never better.

428
00:26:38.221 --> 00:26:39.722
He says he feels younger every day

429
00:26:39.806 --> 00:26:42.725
and that a dollar buys
a thousand dollars' worth of stuff.

430
00:26:43.143 --> 00:26:46.186
Of course. they need that with
all the medication Bev takes.

431
00:26:46.271 --> 00:26:47.813
but. um. yeah.

432
00:26:48.440 --> 00:26:50.858
No. I... No. I see the appeal.

433
00:26:51.318 --> 00:26:52.610
Apparently. there's zero crime.

434
00:26:52.694 --> 00:26:53.986
I keep telling your mother.

435
00:26:54.070 --> 00:26:56.071
Yeah. it's very safe.

436
00:26:58.199 --> 00:26:59.700
We worry.

437
00:27:00.619 --> 00:27:03.495
PAUL: When I was younger.
and then I lost it.

438
00:27:03.580 --> 00:27:04.747
(ALL LAUGHING)

439
00:27:04.831 --> 00:27:05.831
Hey.

440
00:27:06.541 --> 00:27:08.626
You guys are the ones
getting small. right?

441
00:27:10.795 --> 00:27:12.921
That's right. My wife and I.

442
00:27:13.465 --> 00:27:14.798
Good for you.

443
00:27:17.719 --> 00:27:19.887
No offense. but. um.

444
00:27:20.639 --> 00:27:23.015
do you think if you're that small.
you should still have

445
00:27:23.099 --> 00:27:26.143
all the same rights
as the rest of us normal-sized people?

446
00:27:26.227 --> 00:27:27.770
I mean. like the right to vote?

447
00:27:30.231 --> 00:27:33.067
- Why wouldn't we?
- Oh. well. jeez. let's see...

448
00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:34.777
You're not buying as many products.

449
00:27:34.861 --> 00:27:36.528
you're not paying as much sales tax.

450
00:27:36.613 --> 00:27:38.697
Some of you aren't even paying
any income tax.

451
00:27:38.865 --> 00:27:40.324
You're not really participating

452
00:27:40.408 --> 00:27:41.533
- in our economy. are you?
- PAUL: Hey.

453
00:27:41.618 --> 00:27:44.036
In fact. you're costing us
money. and jobs.

454
00:27:44.204 --> 00:27:45.954
Hey! That's enough.

455
00:27:46.581 --> 00:27:48.123
We're just having a good time here.

456
00:27:48.708 --> 00:27:51.043
Hey. I'm just asking a simple
academic question.

457
00:27:51.294 --> 00:27:52.294
You know what?

458
00:27:52.379 --> 00:27:53.962
You guys should have
a quarter of the vote at most.

459
00:27:54.047 --> 00:27:55.547
That's pretty generous. don't you think?

460
00:27:55.632 --> 00:27:56.882
- Why don't you have a seat?
- Whoa. whoa. whoa.

461
00:27:56.966 --> 00:27:59.134
- Why don't you take a walk?
- Cool your jets. big guy!

462
00:27:59.302 --> 00:28:01.470
You know what? Maybe
an eighth of a vote. in fact.

463
00:28:01.638 --> 00:28:03.514
And you could use a little small. buddy.

464
00:28:03.598 --> 00:28:04.807
Yeah. sit down.

465
00:28:06.601 --> 00:28:08.227
Hey! Hey!

466
00:28:08.895 --> 00:28:12.398
Can I get a normal-sized beer
for a normal-sized guy?

467
00:28:55.608 --> 00:28:57.317
(SIGHS)

468
00:29:18.923 --> 00:29:21.341
I keep thinking I forgot something.

469
00:29:28.183 --> 00:29:30.184
(INDISTINCT ANNOUNCEMENT ON PA)

470
00:29:35.815 --> 00:29:37.399
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

471
00:29:58.087 --> 00:29:59.922
Moving to town. are you?

472
00:30:00.965 --> 00:30:01.965
How's that?

473
00:30:02.509 --> 00:30:04.927
I see you're moving to Leisureland.

474
00:30:05.303 --> 00:30:07.304
You look like a nice young couple.

475
00:30:08.765 --> 00:30:09.765
Thanks.

476
00:30:09.933 --> 00:30:12.017
- Where you from?
- Uh. Omaha.

477
00:30:12.435 --> 00:30:13.769
Spokane.

478
00:30:14.229 --> 00:30:15.312
Nervous?

479
00:30:16.439 --> 00:30:19.024
Yeah. you know. a little.

480
00:30:19.275 --> 00:30:23.278
Don't be. It's the best thing
you'll ever do.

481
00:30:28.743 --> 00:30:30.911
<i>ADMINISTRATOR:
With your permission. I'm going to</i>

482
00:30:30.995 --> 00:30:33.747
<i>record your answers
to the following questions.</i>

483
00:30:34.082 --> 00:30:35.791
May I begin the recording?

484
00:30:35.875 --> 00:30:37.042
PAUL: Sure.
AUDREY: Yeah.

485
00:30:40.129 --> 00:30:42.548
Please state your full legal names.

486
00:30:43.341 --> 00:30:45.425
Audrey Lustig Safranek.

487
00:30:46.177 --> 00:30:48.345
Paul Norris Safranek.

488
00:30:48.930 --> 00:30:52.015
And do you. Audrey Lustig Safranek.

489
00:30:52.267 --> 00:30:55.102
and you. Paul Norris Safranek.

490
00:30:55.353 --> 00:30:58.272
understand that.
of your own free will. you will undergo

491
00:30:58.523 --> 00:31:01.108
the permanent and
irreversible medical procedure

492
